04833nam a2200733Ia 9780520342057DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232010cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203420577 a10.1525/97805203420572doi  a(DE-B1597)565533  a(OCoLC)1224278111  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHV6474 7aSOC0310002bisacsh04a364.15089qOCoLC221/eng/202302161 aHorowitz, Donald L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Deadly Ethnic Riot /cDonald L. Horowitz.  aReprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (605 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tA Note on Place Names -- t1. Say It with Murder -- t2. Ethnic Boundaries, Riot Boundaries -- t3. The Riot Episode -- t4. Selective Targeting -- t5. Target-Group Characteristics -- t6. An Economy of Antipathy: Target Selection and the Imperatives of Violence -- t7. Organizers and Participants -- t8. The Occasions for Violence -- t9. The Social Environment for Killing -- t10. Location, Diffusion, and Recurrence -- t11. Aims, Effects, and Functions -- t12. Violence and Quiescence -- t13. The Calculus of Passion -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDonald L. Horowitz's comprehensive consideration of the structure and dynamics of ethnic violence is the first full-scale, comparative study of what the author terms the deadly ethnic riot—an intense, sudden, lethal attack by civilian members of one ethnic group on civilian members of another ethnic group. Serious, frequent, and destabilizing, these events result in large numbers of casualties. Horowitz examines approximately 150 such riots in about fifty countries, mainly in Asia, Africa, and the former Soviet Union, as well as fifty control cases. With its deep and thorough scholarship, incisive analysis, and profound insights, The Deadly Ethnic Riot will become the definitive work on its subject. Furious and sadistic, the riot is nevertheless directed against a precisely specified class of targets and conducted with considerable circumspection. Horowitz scrutinizes target choices, participants and organization, the timing and supporting conditions for the violence, the nature of the events that precede the riot, the prevalence of atrocities during the violence, the location and diffusion of riots, and the aims and effects of riot behavior. He finds that the deadly ethnic riot is a highly patterned but emotional event that tends to occur during times of political uncertainty. He also discusses the crucial role of rumor in triggering riots, the surprisingly limited role of deliberate organization, and the striking lack of remorse exhibited by participants. Horowitz writes clearly and eloquently without compromising the complexity of his subject. With impressive analytical skill, he takes up the important challenge of explaining phenomena that are at once passionate and calculative.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCulture conflict. 0aEthnic relations. 0aEthnicity. 0aRiots. 0aSocial conflict. 0aViolence. 4acontrol. 4aemotion. 4aethnic studies. 4aminorities. 4anature. 4aorganization. 4apolitical science. 4apress. 4asocial aspects. 4asociology. 4astructure. 4aviolence. 4awork. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520342057?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520342057423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520342057/original  a978-3-11-069